{#
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Projects are Markdown files in content/projects/ — this page only lists
  them. To add one, create e.g. content/projects/my-project.md.

  Project order is set in content/projects/order.json — an array of project
  filenames (without ".md") listed top-to-bottom. Anything not listed falls to
  the end (alphabetically by title). Projects have no date.

  Front-matter fields:
    Required:  title        — heading + list-link text
    Optional:  description  — one-line summary under the title in the list;
                              supports inline Markdown links, e.g. [text](url)
               logo         — small icon shown inline before the title
               website      — the project's default/primary link (like an
                              experience's). The list title opens the detail
                              page (→); on the detail page the title links here
                              (↗). Use this for the one main link.
               links        — additional external links (GitHub / Devpost / live
                              site / …), each { label, url }; shown as a row of
                              "label ↗" links on both the list and detail page

  Body features (all optional Markdown):
    • Paragraphs            — render as justified prose on the detail page
    • Inline links          — [text](https://example.com), underlined-redirect style
    • Blockquote pull-quote — > line, with an optional <cite>— Attribution</cite>;
                              the attribution can hold a link, e.g.
                              > <cite>— [Author](https://example.com)</cite>
    • Standalone image      — alone in its own paragraph; becomes a <figure>, and
                              an image "title" in quotes becomes its <figcaption>.
                              The caption supports inline Markdown, so links work:
                              "Caption with a [link](https://example.com)" — use
                              Markdown link syntax, not raw <a> (quotes break it)
    • Inline image          — inside a sentence; stays a plain <img>, no figure

  Each .md file automatically gets its own detail page and joins the
  scroll-through navigation for this section (in projectOrder.json order).

  Reference entry (it never renders here; copy it into a new .md file):

      ---
      title: Project One
      description: A one-line summary of the project.
      links:
        - label: GitHub
          url: https://github.com/yourhandle/project-one
        - label: Devpost
          url: https://devpost.com/software/project-one
        - label: Live
          url: https://example.com
      ---

      A normal paragraph of body copy (Markdown).

      A paragraph with an inline [link](https://example.com).

      > A blockquote becomes a styled pull-quote.
      >
      > <cite>— Some Author</cite>

      ![alt text](/img/projects/project-one/photo-1.webp "Optional caption")

      Here is an inline image ![alt](/img/projects/project-one/photo-2.webp) in a sentence.
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#}
